This paper presents a new method for analyzing the running time of parallel evolutionary algorithms, which are commonly used in the field of computational intelligence and optimization. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). The paper also discusses migration topologies, which are related to graph theory and distributed computing, suggesting that cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) are also likely sub-categories. The fitness-level method used in the paper involves analyzing the expected behavior of the algorithm, which is related to probability and statistics, suggesting that cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the speedup gained by parallelization, which is related to performance analysis and optimization, suggesting that cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is also a possible sub-category.
